{
  "blocks": [
    {
      "type": "headline",
      "text": "Point Affidavit.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 0,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "subheadline",
      "text": "FOR GENERAL PURPOSES IN UNITED STATES CLAIM BUSINESS.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 20,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "A NEW RULE.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 40,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The Department at Washington have made a new rule, requiring where witnesses sign their names to an affidavit by making their mark (x) that two persons who can write, must attest such signatures by signing to the left side of the names of the affiants making a mark. The officer administering the rule cannot be used for obtaining parties. Thus, his example.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 60,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 60
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Attest",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 120,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "JOHN BROWN,",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 140,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "JOSEPH SMITH.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 160,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Sworn to, subscribed, &c.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 180,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "AMOS HIPLEY,",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 200,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Justice Peace",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 220,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "As the parties making oath to this paper sign their names by mark (x) wherever such mark is made there must be two persons who write their names to attend the same. This requirement is now inflexible and cannot be departed from, as the Government Offices will reject any affidavit or other paper offered as evidence wherein marks are made for signatures of the marks are not properly attested as herein named. The agent of these Directives does not add precise proprietor knowledge.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 240,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 80
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "We, A. J. Hicks Jr. and W. D. Chambers, each of lawful age, and residents of the (1) County of Henderson, in the State of Kentucky, upon our oaths declare that we were personally and well acquainted with Aaron Chambers, Dec'd., late a private in Co. \"F\" 18th Regt. U. S. C. I. Infty., who died, as we verily believe, while in the U. S. service on or about the 6th day of November 1864. We also state that we are well acquainted with Rose Chambers, who is making application for army pension, as widow of aforesaid Aaron Chambers, and know that she is the true and lawful widow of said soldier, Dec'd. That they were never formally married for the reason that the laws of Kentucky did not require a license and record or formal marriage for persons of color, but recognized them as man and wife from the act of co'dition. That the aforesaid Rose and Aaron Chambers commenced living together as man and wife on or about 15th day of March AD 1837, and continued to live together as such until the decease of aforesaid Aaron, according to custom of persons of color in the State of Kentucky. That we have often heard said Aaron Chambers call her (Rose Chambers) \"wife,\" and always treated and respected her in such relation. That they were considered as man and wife by all their neighbors and acquaintances, and considered respectable in the community in which they lived. That there are now living none of their (said Aaron and Rose Chambers) under the age of sixteen years. And that she has been a widow since the death of above named soldier (Aaron Chambers), Dec'd.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 320,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 200
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "That we have no interest in this matter.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 520,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "A. J. Hicks Jr. (1)",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 540,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "W. D. Chambers (2)",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 560,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Sworn to and subscribed before me, this Sixteenth day of September in the year 1867, and I hereby certify that the affiants are respectable and credible persons and reside as stated; that I believe their statements are correct and worthy of full faith and credit; and that I have no interest in this matter. I further certify that the foregoing affidavit was read over, fully explained to, and understood by the affiants before the signing and direction thereof.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 580,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 80
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "A. J. Hicks (3)",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 660,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "N. P. H. Co. Ky.",
      "bbox": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 680,
        "width": 100,
        "height": 20
      }
    }
  ]
}
